The last chapter is devoted to Cihuatlampa, "land of the women" and with khan Tonatiuh Ilhuicac, "sky house of the sun." Close to the earth and to the moon, the first netherworld was populated by women who died in labor and who accompanied the sun in the western part of its course. Ragot describes in detail these Cihuateteo, divine women assimilated to warriors, frightening seductresses associated with dirt, sexual transgressions, and diseases. As for the solar paradise of the warriors, it is conceived as a desert plain identified with a battlefield. Accompa­nying the sun to the zenith, transformed into birds and butterflies in the afternoon in Tamoanchan, the warriors killed in war or on the stone of sacrifice are carrying the sky aloft but are also menacing stars in the night. Start­ing from this cyclic model worked out by Graulich, Ragot specifies the functions of these dead, the "divine food" of the star, and examines in detail the Tzitzimime, little­known malefic creatures who originated in the transfor­mation of the warriors and the Cihuateteo. 
Precise and well documented, Ragot's book fills in a gap in the Mesoamerican literature. One can only regret that the iconographic approaches, outlined for example in connection with Mictlantecuhtli, were not developed more fully. In spite of this minor reservation, Les au-de las azteques constitutes an indispensable reference on one of the most fundamental topics for understanding Mesoamerican cosmovision. 
