In other respects, the reader could also wish for more 
attention to gender issues. Tezcatlipoca is an ambiguous 
character, presented as the archetypal male warrior, the 
seducer of the love goddess and the father of the com, 
and yet also sometimes referred to as a homosexual divin­ity. Gender relations and gender identity seem to be at the heart of Tezcatlipoca symbolism, but no chapter is specifically dedicated to this topic. Moreover, some assumptions are quite rapidly taken for granted, such as Tezcatlipoca being a "provider of women" because he is the god of war. Ruiz de Alarcon (Tratado de las super­sticiones, 1987) reports a seducer spell in which the cou­ple appears as Tezcatlipoca and Xochiquetzal, and where the seducer presents himself as a young man weeping for the beauty of the women he wants to enchant. Is he not acknowledging that he is not a warrior (ahmo nelli niyaotl, "I am not really Yaotl" [Enemy, a name of Tez­catlipoca related to war])? Is there a source stating that the ahuianime, the female companions of the warriors, are prisoners of war? What is the marrying pattern between members of conquering and vanquished cities? These issues are complex and certainly deserve a metic­ulous inquiry in the sources and scholarly works. On a broader perspective, this type of shortcoming may be an effect of the tendency shared by many symbolic analy­ses to underplay the social context in which these sym­
bols are created, transformed, and used. 
These few criticisms should not prevent one from reading Moqueries et metamorphoses. On the contrary, there is a need for more work of this kind and quality. Nahuatl symbolism is extremely rich and multivocal and is layered by centuries of symbol building and borrow­ing. Exhaustive studies of narrow and well-defined aspects of this fascinating religious thought, like Olivier's work on one god, are indispensable for a better under­standing of ancient Nahuatl religion. 
